[i]Osomatsu-kun[/i] (おそ松くん?) is a manga series by [[Akatsuka Fujio]] which ran in Shōnen Sunday from 1962 to 1969. It has been adapted into two different anime series of the same name, the first in 1966, produced by Studio Zero, and the second in 1988, produced by Pierrot and aired across Japan on Fuji Television and the anime satellite television network, Animax.

title: erlkoenig
body:
German ballad-poem by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe depicting a father desperately riding with his sick son through a forest while being assailed by a (possibly imaginary) supernatural fae creature.

Originally written in 1782 as part of the Singpiel (folk opera play, roughly) [i]Die Fischerin[/i],  [i]Erlkönig[/i] is widely considered Goethe's most famous work. It is often a required reading in German schools, as well as in advanced German classes for people taking German as a second language. 

The ballad has also been set to music by many different famous composers, with Franz Schubert's version (composed in 1815) being most prominent. Several illustrations of [i]Erlkönig[/i] also exist; these tend to depict the father riding desperately while clutching his son, with the titular Erlkönig ("Elf King") levitating in hot pursuit. 

[i]Erlkönig[/i] is known as 魔王 ("Maou", Demon King) in Japanese. Authorship in Japanese sources is sometimes misattributed to Schubert. 

h4. External links

title: la_serena_de_la_noche_(merryweather)
body:
[[Original]] character by [[Merryweather]], [[AT2.]] and "ironmouse":[https://twitter.com/ironmouse]. La Serena de la Noche is an anthropomorphic (and genderbent) representation of [i]El sereno de la noche[/i] (lit. "night dew"), the [b]humid outdoor air at night[/b], which in Latin-American folklore is believed to contain "bad air" or "evil spirits" that can cause sickness. This makes Serena a humanoid miasma spirit of the night.

Serena appears as a massively [[tall_female|tall]] [[dark-skinned_female|Hispanic woman]] with [[long hair|long]] [[brown hair|dark brown]] hair and [[aqua eyes|turquoise eyes]]. She has turquoise teardrop-shaped [[earrings]]. She wears a low-cut [[lace-trimmed dress|lace-trimmed]] [[black dress]] (inside colored turquoise) with [[elbow gloves|elbow-length]] [[black gloves]] and [[high heels]]. She also wears a black [[veil]] and a wide-brimmed [[black headwear|black]] [[hat]] (again, inside colored turqoise). Overall she resembles [[Hasshaku-sama]] but with a darker color scheme.

Serena also carries a normal-sized (appearing small in her hands) [[spear]] with a lantern hanging off near the spear tip. This is a reference to historical [i]sereno[/i] nightwatchmen, who were known to also carry a similar style of spear and lantern in Latin America.

title: ankle_lock
body:
A wrestling move where the wrestler applies pressure to the opponent's ankle and lifts it from the ground. With one hand the wrestler will grab either the toes or the outside of the foot, then with the other wrap the ankle to create a "hole" for the joint. 

A grapevine variation sees the wrestler applying the ankle lock hold and then falling to the mat and scissoring the leg of the opponent. This stops the opponent from rolling out of the move and makes it harder for him/her to crawl to the ropes but lessens the pressure that can be applied. The move can be executed from a kneeling position or a standing position.

Popular users of this move are Ken Shamrock, Kurt Angle, Jake Hager and Shelton Benjamin.

title: fujiwara_takumi
body:
The protagonist of [[Initial D]]. Often seen driving his iconic two-tone panda [[Toyota Sprinter Trueno]].

Takumi is somewhat pokey and can come off as awkward or dense, but is a natural behind the wheel and possesses an almost symbiotic relationship with his car - a result of being made to drive it from a very early age, day in and out, be it clear, rainy or snowy, up and down the mountain road next to his town to deliver tofu to the mountaintop hotel for his father, [[Fujiwara Bunta]].

title: inui_shinji
body:
The final opponent of [[Fujiwara Takumi]] in [[Initial D]]. 

Shinji is essentially a mirror-match of Takumi's initial appearance: a young boy (either 15 or 16), in an underpowered [[Toyota Sprinter Trueno]], who has been driving from a very early age (in this case, to relieve his overworked mother) and has an almost-unnatural feel for his home course, the Tsubaki Line, enabling him to drive extremely fast for somewhat childish reasons (Takumi's high speed runs came as a result of him wanting to be done with tofu deliveries faster, whereas Shinji has an odd fixation with braking as little as possible and has experience on both sides of the road due to going to school on the passenger side while his mother drove him there and returning home behind the wheel).

Due to his very young age, Shinji is prone to somewhat childish outbursts (such as being too nervous to show up on time for his race against Takumi, or intentionally allowing a rival to pass so he could show off an overtake) and sometimes daydreams of "wings" on Takumi's car.

A bitter alcoholic, he apathetically helped Zouken do his bidding, by acclimating [[Matou Sakura|Sakura]] to the worms and training her to be worthy of becoming the next head of the Matou house. Despite this, he's very determined to keep his son away from the truths of the Matou family, so he sends him to study abroad when the 4th Grail War starts.

Byakuya died 3 years prior to the events of [[Fate/Stay Night]]. He kept hiding more things from Shinji, such as the truth of Sakura's adoption. After he accidentally finds the worms basement and the truth about the Matou family, Byakuya cuts all ties with his son and dies shortly after.

Unbeknownst to him, she perished during the cataclysm five hundred years ago, never to resurface. According to Kazari, the kitsune tricked him into playing as to protect Ioroi from evil forces.

As he grew impatient, Ioroi tried to cause ruckus to trick the kitsune into coming back. He even stole a comb used to perform the cleansing sakura ritual. Instead, a human came and sealed him into stone, transforming him into a stone statue and giving him a fear of humans.

In the same way that mercury is harmful to human beings (due to its toxicity) and destructive to metals such as aluminum (due to forming amalgams that compromise their strength), Cinnabar's very presence is hazardous to their fellow Gems. title: yamato-no-kami_yasusada
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character. Official art by [[kumita_(sumica)|Kumita]]. Voiced by [[Ichiki Mitsuhiro]].

Both he and [[Kashuu Kiyomitsu]] are personifications of swords owned by [[Okita Souji]]. Unlike Kiyomitsu, who resents Okita for abandoning him, Yasusada is very fond of Okita and hasn't gotten over his former master's death, to the point of dressing and occasionally acting like him. 

He has [[black hair]] worn in a [[high ponytail]], [[blue eyes]], and a [[mole under eye|mole under his left eye]]. His standard outfit is a [[white scarf]], a [[Shinsengumi]] [[haori]], [[black gloves|black]] "[[bridal gauntlets|bridal gauntlet]]"-type gloves, a dark blue [[hakama]], black [[tabi]] and [[zouri]] with blue straps.

Normally, he has a carefree personality with his comrades, but is ruthless and sadistic in battles. Of course, artists tend to portray him as someone who's completely obsessed with Okita (to the point of being dismissive with the Saniwa) and who gets violent for no reason. Either that, or he's presented as a foil to Kiyomitsu.

There is also [[yamato-no-kami yasusada (ootachi)|another sword called Yamato-no-Kami Yasusada]], which is not currently a character in Touken Ranbu.

title: monpe
body:
A type of women's work [[pants]] from Japan. They are also considered to be a type of [[hakama pants]]. 
The waist is loose to allow the hem of a jacket or other outerwear to be tucked inside, and the ankle cuffs are tightened with strings for ease of movement. 
While they were originally used for agricultural labor in the Tohoku region, during the [[World War II]], the Ministry of Welfare encouraged all women in Japan to wear them, and as the state of the war worsened, their wearing was substantively enforced and made mandatory for fire fighting work during air raids. 

On pixiv, this tag is often used for [[pants]] of [[Fujiwara no Mokou]] and [[Kazami Yuuka (PC-98)]]. 
[quote]If you try searching this tag on pixiv, you will find chaotic mixture of [[war]]-related artworks and [[Touhou]] illustrations. 
-- from pixiv encyclopedia 
[/quote]

title: gyeongsang_korean_text
body:
Korean dialect spoken in the Gyeongsang region.

This dialect is characterized by merging of [i]ae[/i] and [i]e[/i], as well as [i]eu[/i] and [i]eo[/i], plus dropping of [i]w[/i] and [i]y[/i] (/j/) after consonants. Southern Gyeongsang also lacks the "tense" fortis consonant [i]ss[/i] of Standard Korean; speakers will instead substitute it with a "lax" [i]s[/i].

Southern Gyeongsang (especially the Busan variant) is frequently used in translations and fanworks to adapt Japanese [[Kansaiben]] (analogous to use of Southern American English in English translations and fanworks). Japanese characters who speak Kansai dialect are frequently depicted speaking Busan dialect in Korean translations and fancomics.

h4. See also

* [[Kansaiben]]
